	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">UncleSporky wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I have the same lack of remorse for players who don't read the manual and get upset when they don't know how to jump, or who skip the "boring tutorial" and get upset when they don't know how to equip an item...or those who don't watch a scene that gives them vital information.</div><br /><br />Addressed in a previous post.</div><br />Enlighten me, because I see no arguments against this.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">In short, the player has responsibility to absorb the information I give him if he wants to enjoy my game. I'm not a bad designer if he refuses my help. </div><br /><br />You're a bad designer for insisting upon a way to help that people are likely to refuse.  A better designer would do a better job of helping.</div><br />How do you know people are likely to refuse?  All I know from this topic is the anecdotal report of one Disch who would refuse.  According to my own anecdotal research, everyone else I know would watch the scene.<br /><br />Again, bad is relative.  Maybe I change my game so that all vital information is now on signposts throughout the world.  Now the 3 people who don't watch cutscenes are satisfied, but the 10 people who think signs break immersion hate it.  Now I've had a net loss of players just because I tried to placate one person.  Thanks a lot!<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But why intentionally alienate people by forcing them watch cutscenes when you can just as easily present the same information in a more interesting / easier to absorb way?</div><br />I'm not intentionally alienating anyone, anymore than by deciding to make a racing game I'm intentionally alienating everyone who hates racers.  All I'm doing is making a game, and it's up to any individual if they like it or not.<br /><br />"More interesting / easier to absorb" is relative.  Some people love to read manuals.  Some people want fully voice acted, integrated-with-the-storyline tutorials.  That's pretty expensive and time consuming and I'm not "intentionally alienating" them by leaving it out.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The thing is these games <em>don't need to be</em> cinematic.  I love the gameplay in Cave Story.  It's tons of fun.<br /><br />The problem with it is that the cutscenes are not skippable.  I've seen them all several times.  I can't play the game anymore because I find it tiresome to repeatedly tap the action button and wait for those scenes to end.  It's a <em>serious</em> replay killer, and a <em>serious</em> flaw in the game.<br /><br /><br />There is absolutely no reason those cutscenes shouldn't have been skippable.  It was a terrible design decision to make them nonskippable.</div><br />As there is no objective measurement for quality in a game, one man's serious flaw is another's favorite part.  You have no right to call anything a flaw unless you keep in mind that you don't speak for anyone else.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Konami makes long, drawn out, highly complicated cutscenes in Metal Gear because they know their target audience wants that.</div><br /><br />And they'd be wrong if they didn't make their cut scenes skippable.</div>
<br />Wrong according to one Disch.  Everyone else is just fine with learning important information in their cutscenes.
<br />
<br />When you think about it, a majority of cutscenes relay important information, and players who don't watch them are at a disadvantage.  In Metal Gear it can be the simple fact of showing players the layout of the room prior to fighting a boss, as well as alerting them that a boss fight is starting.  People who skip the scene before it have no right to complain when they get shot in the chest after they choose "skip."
<br />
<br />Or even Mario games.  The Galaxy games give you a quick flyby of the level as you first enter it, showing you the layout and potentially the location of hidden items.  If I accidentally press a button and skip it, it doesn't make them bad designers for not including a "watch intro flyby again" button on the pause screen.  They've got signs and NPCs everywhere explaining things you need to do; it doesn't make them a bad designer if I find this immersion-breaking.  It makes me a picky player, just as your own opinions make you a picky player.

		

		</td>
