		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />For what it's worth, I'm in agreement with Disch here.  Making cutscenes or drama-scenes (think Ninja Gaiden) skippable is more or less a requirement.  If the player/user wants to skip said scenes, they'll press a button/whatever.  If they don't, that's their choice too.  If the scene in question is actually a training sequence and they skip it, so what -- it's their own fault/demise.
<br />
<br />The modus operandi for not permitting cutscene skipping seems to be either paranoia or vengeance; I can't tell which.
<br />
<br />Do you know how many NES and SNES games I've played where I've skipped tutorials, cut-scenes, etc. simply to get back to the gameplay -- instead referring to the user manual for details?  Many.  :-)

		

